<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-sensitivity">
	<title>Sensitivity to change</title>

	<objectives>
		<ol>
			<li>
				<p>
					Measure a function's responsiveness to small changes using ratios.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					Visualize the sensitivity of a function as a ratio of differentials.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					Use the sign and value of the sensitivity to estimate changes in the dependent variable.
				</p>
			</li>
		</ol>
	</objectives>

	<introduction>
		<p>
			Calculus is often described as the mathematics of change. Many quantities in the world change in tandem with each other:
		</p>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<p>
					The pressure of a gas depends on its temperature and volume.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The demand for a product depends on its price.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The daily calories needed by an organism depends on its mass.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The speed of a car depends on the pressure applied to the gas pedal.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The growth of a bacterial population depends on the amount of nutrients available.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The amount of traffic congestion depends on the number of cars on the road.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The brightness of a lamp depends on the electrical power supplied to it.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					The time for a computer to sort a list depends on the number of items in the list.
				</p>
			</li>
		</ul>
		<p>
			To understand these relationships, we need a way to quantify how <em>sensitive</em> one quantity is to changes in another: if we change one variable by a small amount, how much does another variable change in response?
		</p>
	</introduction>
	
	<subsection xml:id="subsec-sensitivity-between-two-points">
		<title>Sensitivity between two points</title>
		<aside>
			<p>
				Based on data from <url href="https://arachnoid.com/braking_physics/index.html">The Physics Behind Stopping a Car</url> by P. Lutus.
			</p>
		</aside>
		<p>
			When driving a car, the distance required to stop depends on the speed of the vehicle. If <m>L</m> is the stopping distance (measured in car lengths, assuming an average car length of <m>14.7</m> feet), and <m>v</m> is the speed (measured in miles per hour), then the relationship between <m>L</m> and <m>v</m> can be modeled by the formula
			<me>
				L = 0.0034v^2 + 0.15v
			</me>.
			To make it explicit that <m>L</m> depends on <m>v</m> (that is, <m>L</m> is a <term>function</term> of <m>v</m>), we can also write
			<me>
				L(v) = 0.0034v^2 + 0.15v
			</me>.
			We call <m>v</m> the <term>independent variable</term> and <m>L</m> or <m>L(v)</m> the <term>dependent variable</term>, since the value of <m>L</m> depends on the value of <m>v</m>.
		</p>
		<aside>
			<p>
				In general, when one quantity depends on another, there are two common ways to name this relationship. We can name the output directly, as in <m>y</m> depending on <m>x</m> and writing <m>y = y(x)</m>, or we can give the function a separate name and write <m>y = f(x)</m>.
			</p>
		</aside>
		<p>
			For example, if a car is traveling at <m>50</m> miles per hour, we have
			<md>
				<mrow>L(50) \amp = 0.0034\cdot 50^2 + 0.15\cdot 50</mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = 16 \text{ car lengths}</mrow>
			</md>,
			so the model predicts a stopping distance of <m>16</m> car lengths (or approximately <m>235.2</m> feet).
		</p>
		<image width="75%">
			<prefigure label="stopping-distance" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
				<diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
				<definition>f(x)=0.0034*x^2+0.15*x</definition>
				<definition>a = 50</definition>
				<definition>b = 55</definition>
				<coordinates bbox="(-10,-10,70,70)">
					<grid-axes xlabel="v" ylabel="L(v)"/>
					<graph at="graph" function="f" domain="(0,75)"/>
					<point p="(a,f(a))" alignment="ne"/>
				</coordinates>
				</diagram>
			</prefigure>
		</image>
		<p>
			Now, we might wonder, if we were to change the speed, how much would the stopping distance change? For example, suppose the speed increases by five miles per hour, that is,
			<md>
				<mrow>\Delta v \amp = v\tsub{final} - v\tsub{init}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 55 - 50</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 5 \text{ mph}</mrow>
			</md>.
			
			Then the change in stopping distance would be
			<md>
				<mrow>\Delta L \amp = L\tsub{final} - L\tsub{init}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = L(55) - L(50)</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = (0.0034\cdot 55^2 + 0.15\cdot 55) - (0.0034\cdot 50^2 + 0.15\cdot 50)</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 2.535\text{ car lengths}</mrow>
			</md>.
			We can then find the <em>ratio</em> of the change in stopping distance to the change in speed:
			<md>
				<mrow>\frac{\Delta L}{\Delta v} \amp = \frac{L(55) - L(50)}{55-50}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = \frac{2.535\text{ car lengths}}{5\text{ mph}}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 0.507\text{ car lengths per mph}</mrow>
			</md>.
			That is, an extra mile per hour of speed means it takes another half of a car length to stop. We can call this the <term>sensitivity</term> of the stopping distance to the given change in speed.
		</p>
		<definition>
			<title>Sensitivity between two points</title>

			<statement>
				<p>
					If <m>y=f(x)</m>, then the <term>sensitivity</term> of <m>f</m> between the points <m>x=a</m> and <m>x=b</m> is defined as
					<me>
						\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x} = \frac{f(b) - f(a)}{b - a}
					</me>.
					
					That is, the sensitivity is the ratio of the change in the output to the change in the input over that interval. We often say this out loud as <sq>the sensitivity of <m>y</m> to changes in <m>x</m>.</sq>
				</p>
				<p>
					We will also use the notation <m>\dfrac{\Delta f}{\Delta x}</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>

		<p>
			We can also visualize what we've just done by plotting the stopping distance function <m>L(v)</m>:
		</p>
		<aside>
			<p>
				Will figure out how to make this graph better.
			</p>
		</aside>
		<image width="75%">
			<prefigure label="stopping-distance-sensitivity-interval" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
				<diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
				<definition>f(x)=0.0034*x^2+0.15*x</definition>
				<definition>a = 50</definition>
				<definition>b = 55</definition>
				<coordinates bbox="(-10,-10,70,70)">
					<grid-axes xlabel="v" ylabel="L(v)"/>
					<graph at="graph" function="f" domain="(0,75)"/>
					<line p1="(a,f(a))" p2="(b,f(a))"/>
					<line p1="(b,f(a))" p2="(b,f(b))"/>
					<point p="(a,f(a))" alignment="ne"/>
					<point p="(b,f(b))" alignment="ne"/>
				</coordinates>
				</diagram>
			</prefigure>
		</image>
		<p>
			Notice that the sensitivity we've calculated is the <em>slope</em> of the line segment connecting the points <m>(v\tsub{init},L\tsub{init})</m> and <m>(v\tsub{final},L\tsub{final})</m>.
		</p>
	</subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="subsec-sensitivity-at-a-point">
		<title>Sensitivity at a point</title>
		<p>
			Our calculation of the sensitivity above was somewhat coarse: the graph of <m>L(v)</m> is curved, and over an increase of five miles per hour, the slope gets gradually steeper as we go. In other words, our calculation seems to mix together several sensitivities.
		</p>
		<p>
			If we want a more fine-grained measurement, a natural idea is to look at smaller changes in speed. Here's what happens if we use a change in speed of <m>\Delta v=0.1</m> mph:
			<md>
				<mrow>\frac{\Delta L}{\Delta v} \amp = \frac{L(50.1) - L(50)}{50.1-50}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = \frac{0.049034\text{ car lengths}}{0.1\text{ mph}}</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = 0.49034\text{ car lengths per mph}</mrow>
			</md>.
		</p>
		<activity>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Estimate the sensitivity of the stopping distance to the following changes <m>\Delta v</m> (assuming an initial speed of <m>v\tsub{init}=50</m> mph). What do you notice about the values you get?
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\Delta v=0.01</m> mph
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\Delta v=0.001</m> mph
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\Delta v=-0.1</m> mph
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\Delta v=-0.01</m> mph
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\Delta v=-0.001</m> mph
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</activity>
		<p>
			Over smaller and smaller changes, the graph looks more and more like a straight line, and the slope between the two points appears to approach a particular value, which seems to be around <m>0.49</m> car lengths per mph. (We'll soon learn how to find this value exactly, without having to do so many calculations.)
		</p>
		<p>
			Now, let's ask a bold question: what if we could zoom in <sq>infinitely close</sq> to the point <m>(50,16)</m>?
		</p>
		<p>
			If we could do this, we might imagine that the graph of <m>L(v)</m> would be indistinguishable from a perfectly straight line at that point. So if we could somehow choose two points that are <sq>infinitely close</sq> to each other, then the ratio of the infinitesimal (infinitely small) changes would be the slope of that line:
		</p>
		<image width="75%">
			<prefigure label="stopping-distance-sensitivity-point" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
				<diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
				<definition>f(x)=0.0034*x^2+0.15*x</definition>
				<definition>a = 50</definition>
				<definition>b = 55</definition>
				<coordinates bbox="(-10,-10,70,70)">
					<grid-axes xlabel="v" ylabel="L(v)"/>
					<graph at="graph" function="f" domain="(0,75)"/>
					<point p="(a,f(a))" alignment="ne"/>
				</coordinates>
				</diagram>
			</prefigure>
		</image>
		<p>
			We call these infinitely small changes <term>differentials</term>, and we represent them with a lowercase <m>\mathrm{d}</m>: in this case, we would write <m>\dd{v}</m> to denote an infinitesimal change in speed, and <m>\dd{L}</m> to denote the corresponding infinitesimal change in stopping distance. The ratio of these differentials would then be written <me>\dv{L}{v}</me>. We will call this the <term>sensitivity</term> <em>at the single point</em> where <m>v=50</m> miles per hour.
		</p>
		<definition xml:id="def-sensitivity-at-a-point">
			<title>Sensitivity at a point</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					If <m>y=f(x)</m>, the <term>sensitivity</term> of <m>f</m> at the point <m>x=a</m> is (for the time being) defined as
					<me>
						\dv{y}{x}\approx\frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a}
					</me>
					where <m>b</m> is <sq>infinitely close</sq> to <m>a</m>. This definition is currently somewhat vague, as we have not defined what it means to be <sq>infinitely close.</sq> We'll make this definition more precise later.
				</p>
				<p>
					We will also use the notation <m>\DS\dv{f}{x}</m> for this sensitivity.
				</p>
				<p>
					When we want to emphasize that the sensitivity is being evaluated at a particular point <m>x=a</m>, we will write <m>\eval{\DS\dv{y}{x}}_{x=a}</m> or <m>\eval{\DS\dv{f}{x}}_{x=a}</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>
		<p>
			Now, you might be a bit skeptical of this idea of using <sq>infinitely small</sq> changes. If so, you're in good company! This idea of using infinitesimal quantities has long been a controversial topic in mathematics. On one hand, infinity is notoriously difficult to get a handle on <mdash/> just how small is <sq>infinitely small</sq> anyway? On the other hand, allowing ourselves to work with these infinitesimal ideas has helped us solve a lot of tricky problems throughout history. By developing calculus, we'll be able to find a way to make these intuitive-but-somewhat-vague arguments more precise, which will allow us to use them with confidence to describe real-world phenomena in a variety of applied contexts.
		</p>
		<activity>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Use this same process to estimate <m>\eval{\DS\dv{L}{v}}_{v=30}</m> and <m>\eval{\DS\dv{L}{v}}_{v=70}</m>. How does the sensitivity of stopping distance to changes in speed compare at these different speeds?
				</p>
			</statement>
		</activity>
	</subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="subsec-interpreting-sensitivity">
		<title>Interpreting sensitivity</title>
		<p>
			Let's look at another example. Suppose the following graph shows <m>R</m>, the revenue earned (in thousands of dollars) from selling a product, as a function of <m>p</m>, the price charged (in dollars):
		</p>
		<image width="75%">
			<prefigure label="revenue-price" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
				<diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
				<definition>f(x)=x*(16-x)</definition>
				<definition>a = 50</definition>
				<definition>b = 55</definition>
				<coordinates bbox="(-5,-10,21,80)">
					<grid-axes xlabel="p" ylabel="R(p)"/>
					<graph at="graph" function="f" domain="(0,16)"/>
					<point p="(a,f(a))" alignment="ne"/>
				</coordinates>
				</diagram>
			</prefigure>
		</image>
		<p>
			Even though we don't have an explicit formula for <m>R(p)</m>, we can still determine the sign of the sensitivity <m>\DS\dv{R}{p}</m> by looking at the slope of the graph at each point:
		</p>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<p>
					On the left side of the graph (when <m>p \lt 8</m>), the sensitivity <m>\DS\dv{R}{p}</m> is positive. This means that increasing the price would lead to an increase in revenue, and decreasing the price would lead to a decrease in revenue.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					On the right side of the graph (when <m>p \gt 8</m>), the sensitivity <m>\DS\dv{R}{p}</m> is negative. This means that increasing the price would lead to a <em>decrease</em> in revenue, and decreasing the price would lead to an increase in revenue.
				</p>
			</li>
		</ul>

		<p>
			So looking at the <em>sign</em> of the sensitivity can tell us the <em>direction</em> in which our function responds to changes. We can also use it to tell <em>how much</em> the revenue will change to a small change in price. For example, suppose that at a price of $10, the sensitivity is <me>\eval{\DS\dv{R}{p}}_{p=10} = -4\text{ thousand dollars earned per dollar charged}</me>.
			Now suppose we want to raise the price from $10 to $10.50. Since the sensitivity <m>\DS\dv{R}{p}</m> is supposed to be the ratio of <sq>infinitely small</sq> changes, we can write:
			<me>
				\dfrac{\Delta R}{\Delta p} \approx \DS\dv{R}{p}
			</me>
			Then we can rearrange the terms to get
			<me>
				\Delta R \approx \DS\dv{R}{p}\cdot \Delta p
			</me>.
			Substituting what we know, we have
			<md>
				<mrow>\Delta R \amp \approx -4\cdot 0.5</mrow>
				<mrow>\amp = -2\text{ thousand dollars}</mrow>.
			</md>
			Hence if we increase the price from $10 to $10.50, we can estimate that the revenue will decrease by approximately $2,000.
		</p>
		<p>
			Again, notice that we were able to make this estimation without having an explicit formula for <m>R(p)</m>. In many cases, we don't have a formula for the function we're interested in, such as when our model is based on data. In those cases, understanding how sensitivity lets us estimate change is useful for making predictions in how the output will respond to a change in input.
		</p>
		<activity>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Suppose that we decide to <em>decrease</em> the price from $10 to $9.50. How much would we estimate the revenue to change? Would it increase or decrease? Use the sensitivity at <m>p=10</m> to justify your answer.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</activity>
	</subsection>

	<exercises>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Suppose <m>y=3x-2</m>, so <m>y</m> is a <term>linear function</term> of <m>x</m>.
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the sensitivity of <m>y</m> to various changes in <m>x</m> by completing the following table.
					</p>
					<tabular halign="center">
						<row header="yes" bottom="minor">
							<cell><m>x=a</m></cell>
							<cell><m>x=b</m></cell>
							<cell><m>\Delta x</m></cell>
							<cell><m>\Delta y</m></cell>
							<cell><m>\dfrac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}</m></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><m>1</m></cell>
							<cell><m>2</m></cell>
							<cell></cell>
							<cell></cell>
							<cell></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><m>1</m></cell>
							<cell><m>1.1</m></cell>
							<cell></cell>
							<cell></cell>
							<cell></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><m>1</m></cell>
							<cell><m>1.01</m></cell>
							<cell></cell>
							<cell></cell>
							<cell></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><m>1</m></cell>
							<cell><m>0.99</m></cell>
							<cell></cell>
							<cell></cell>
							<cell></cell>
						</row>
					</tabular>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What do you notice about the values you get for the sensitivity in each case?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What does <m>\DS\dv{y}{x}</m>, the sensitivity of <m>y</m>, seem to be at the point <m>x=1</m>?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What would be the sensitivity of <m>y</m> at the point <m>x=2</m>? Why? 
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What can you conclude about the sensitivity of <m>y=mx+b</m> at any point <m>x=a</m>? Why?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Suppose <m>y=5</m>, so <m>y</m> is a <term>constant function</term> of <m>x</m>. That is, no matter what the value of <m>x</m> is, the value of <m>y</m> is always <m>5</m>.
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What will <m>\DS\dv{y}{x}</m> be at any point <m>x=a</m>? Why?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What does the graph of <m>y=5</m> look like? How does this graph help you understand the sensitivity of <m>y</m> to changes in <m>x</m>?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						If we rewrite <m>y</m> as <m>0x+5</m>, how does this help you understand the sensitivity of <m>y</m> to changes in <m>x</m>?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						If <m>y=k</m> is a constant function of <m>x</m>, where <m>k</m> is any constant, what will the sensitivity of <m>y</m> be at any point <m>x=a</m>? Why?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Suppose <m>y=x^2</m>, so <m>y</m> is a <term>quadratic function</term> of <m>x</m>.
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Estimate <m>\DS\dv{y}{x}</m> at the point <m>x=1</m> by computing the ratios of small changes in the input and output. As the intervals get smaller and smaller, what number does the sensitivity seem to be approaching?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Repeat the above exercise to estimate <m>\DS\dv{y}{x}</m> at the points <m>x=2</m> and <m>x=3</m>. What do you notice about the values you get for the sensitivity at these different points?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Without doing any calculations, what do you think the sensitivity of <m>y=x^2</m> will be at the point <m>x=0</m>? Why?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Conjecture a formula for <m>\DS\dv{y}{x}</m> at any point <m>x=a</m>. Why do you think this formula is correct?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<title>Extra practice</title>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Estimate <m>\DS\dv{y}{x}</m> for each of the following graphs at the given points by computing the ratios of small changes in the input and output. As the intervals get smaller and smaller, what number do the sensitivities seem to be approaching?
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>y=x^3</m>, at <m>x=-2</m> and <m>x=-1</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>y=\sqrt{x}</m>, at <m>x=9</m> and <m>x=12</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>y=\dfrac{1}{x}</m>, at <m>x=3</m> and <m>x=7</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>y=x^2-5x+4</m>, at <m>x=1</m> and <m>x=4</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					In this exercise, you'll interpret the sign of the sensitivity for various real-world contexts. For each one, determine whether the sensitivity should be positive, negative, or zero, and explain your answer. (Think: if you increase the independent variable, what would you expect to happen to the dependent variable?) Also give the units for the sensitivity.
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\DS\dv{B}{P}</m>, where <m>B=</m> the brightness of a lamp (measured in lumens) and <m>P=</m> the electrical power supplied to the lamp (measured in watts)
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\DS\dv{q}{p}</m>, where <m>q=</m> the number of packages of gourmet coffee beans that are ordered by consumers and <m>p=</m> the price (in dollars per package) of the coffee beans
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\DS\dv{T}{t}</m>, where <m>T=</m> the temperature (in degrees Fahrenheit) of a baked potato and <m>t=</m> the number of minutes for which the potato is left to bake in the oven
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\DS\dv{t}{T}</m>, where <m>t=</m> the number of minutes it takes to fully bake a potato (i.e. to get it to reach a desired temperature) and <m>T=</m> the temperature (in degrees Fahrenheit) of the oven
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\DS\dv{C}{h}</m>, where <m>C=</m> the number of calories in a candy bar and <m>h=</m> the elevation (in feet) of the candy bar above sea level
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Suppose the temperature in the Pacific Ocean can be described by the function <m>T(\ell)</m>, where <m>T</m> is the temperature in degrees Celsius and <m>\ell</m> is the latitude in degrees.
				</p>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Suppose that <m>T(60)=10</m>. Explain what this means in context, including correct units.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Suppose that we also know that <m>\eval{\DS\dv{T}{\ell}}_{\ell=60}=-0.5</m>. Explain what this means in context, including correct units.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Estimate <m>T(62)</m> and <m>T(59)</m> using the sensitivity at <m>\ell=60</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
				The profit earned by a company can be defined as the revenue (the money it brings in) minus the costs (the money it spends). The graph below shows <m>P(x)</m>, the profit (in thousands of dollars) earned by a company as a function of <m>x</m>, the number of units produced (in hundreds of units).
				</p>
				<image width="75%">
					<prefigure label="profit-units" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
						<diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
						<definition>P(x)=-0.5*x^2+15*x-40</definition>
						<coordinates bbox="(-5,-50,32,120)">
							<grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="P(x)"/>
							<graph at="graph" function="P" domain="(0,30)"/>
						</coordinates>
						</diagram>
					</prefigure>
				</image>
			</introduction>

			<task>
				<statement>
				<p>
					For which values of <m>x</m> does <m>P(x)</m> appear to be positive? What about negative? Explain how you can tell from the graph. What do these values mean practically for the company?
				</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						What are the units of <m>\DS\dv{P}{x}</m>?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>

			<task>
				<statement>
				<p>
					For which values of <m>x</m> does <m>\DS\dv{P}{x}</m> appear to be positive? What about negative? Explain how you can tell from the graph. What do these values mean practically for the company?
				</p>
				</statement>
			</task>

			<task>
				<statement>
				<p>
					Based on the graph, about how many units should the company produce in order to maximize profit, and what is that maximum profit? What is <m>\DS\dv{P}{x}</m> at that point?
				</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>

		<exercise>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					A car is driven along a fixed 100-mile route. The table below shows the total amount of energy <m>E</m> used for the trip as a function of the car's speed <m>v</m>. Here <m>v</m> is measured in miles per hour and <m>E</m> is measured in kilowatt-hours.
				</p>
				<tabular halign="center">
					<row header="yes" bottom="minor">
						<cell right="minor"><m>v \text{ (mph)}</m></cell>
						<cell><m>45</m></cell>
						<cell><m>50</m></cell>
						<cell><m>55</m></cell>
						<cell><m>60</m></cell>
						<cell><m>65</m></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell right="minor"><m>E \text{ (kWh)}</m></cell>
						<cell><m>32.4</m></cell>
						<cell><m>31.0</m></cell>
						<cell><m>30.6</m></cell>
						<cell><m>30.9</m></cell>
						<cell><m>31.8</m></cell>
					</row>
				</tabular>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Estimate <m>\eval{\DS\dv{E}{v}}_{v=52}</m> and explain its meaning in context, including correct units.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Use your estimate of <m>\eval{\DS\dv{E}{v}}_{v=52}</m> to estimate the total energy used at <m>v=56</m> mph.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Suppose we know that the energy usage is <em>minimized</em> when <m>v=55</m> mph. What would you expect the value of <m>\DS\dv{E}{v}</m> to be at that speed? Explain.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</exercise>
		<exercise>
			<statement>
				<p>
					How does the sensitivity of <m>y=f(x)</m> from <m>x=a</m> to <m>x=b</m> compare to its sensitivity from <m>x=b</m> to <m>x=a</m>? Explain.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
	</exercises>
</section>

